      Hunterbrook!
   =20
 =20

We talked in November about Hunterbrook, a=C2=A0hedge fund that is also a n=
ewspaper. These are mostly tough economic times for the news industry, and =
Hunterbrook hit upon a differentiated media business model:
=09They would=C2=A0start a newsroom (Hunterbrook Media) to publish general =
news and investigative journalism.=09There=E2=80=99s no paywall and no adve=
rtising.=09But before each investigative piece is published, the newsroom w=
ould send it to Hunterbrook=E2=80=99s affiliated hedge fund (Hunterbrook Ca=
pital), which could trade on the news.=09The hedge fund=E2=80=99s trading p=
rofits can =E2=80=94=C2=A0they hope! =E2=80=94 pay the journalists=E2=80=99=
 salaries.

One way to think of this business model is that Hunterbrook is essentially =
an activist short-selling hedge fund, like Hindenburg Research: It investig=
ates companies, finds problems, shorts the companies, and then noisily publ=
ishes its investigation to draw attention to the problems. But=C2=A0whereas=
 Hindenburg is straightforwardly a short-selling firm, Hunterbrook=E2=80=99=
s news site is at least theoretically independent of its hedge fund, and if=
 it publishes enough good general news then perhaps it can become more wide=
